WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:19.000
Okay, this is Emily Crosby with Mrs. Frankie Adams Johnson, December 6, 2015 in Jackson, Mississippi.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:28.000
We're here with the Civil Rights History Project, sponsored by the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:35.000
And John Bishop is also here doing a recording. Thank you very much for doing the interview with us.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:39.000
Can you tell me when and where you were born and about your family?

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:47.000
Okay, I was born in the little town called Pocahontas, Mississippi. It's about 15 minutes north of here.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:01:11.000
And then I was born there into a family of sharecroppers. And I was suddenly up there and the program had a specific group up there until I was about 12 years old and my books moved to Jackson, Mississippi.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:15.000
What more precipitated there moved to Jackson?

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:25.000
Just a hot life of sharecroppers, my parents. They were separated but I actually was to do it.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:33.000
I'm the daughter of four girls, born into a first marriage of merchant and Adams.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:54.000
My mother was a merchant in my daddy at Easton Adams. And so my mother pretty much doing my upbringing in Pocahontas, Mississippi, I was raised by my mom and the village, really, my mom, my grandparents, my great grandparents.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:02:09.000
So just the rigor of sharecroppers and being a Singaporean, so my mother got pretty much the desire to share Kroppin life and so she was a domestic worker.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:16.000
And so she grabbed our children and moved us to Jackson, Mississippi.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:18.000
