all of the people at Tougaloo,

00:48:33.000 --> 00:48:34.000
you know, people who say,

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:36.000
well, Tougaloo is hotbed of the Civil Rights Movement,

00:48:36.000 --> 00:48:38.000
but everyone at Tougaloo did not necessarily,

00:48:38.000 --> 00:48:40.000
even my quiet director,

00:48:40.000 --> 00:48:42.000
I probably would,

00:48:42.000 --> 00:48:43.000
now that I've met you,

00:48:43.000 --> 00:48:44.000
I know all of those,

00:48:44.000 --> 00:48:45.000
the women,

00:48:45.000 --> 00:48:47.000
I wanted to be regular,

00:48:47.000 --> 00:48:48.000
like them, you know?

00:48:48.000 --> 00:48:49.000
And so when I went back,

00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:50.000
you know,

00:48:50.000 --> 00:48:53.000
doing, doing, doing the false semester,

00:48:53.000 --> 00:48:55.000
so I wanted to take on this character

00:48:55.000 --> 00:48:58.000
what it meant to be a Civil Rights Office,

00:48:58.000 --> 00:48:59.000
a SNCC work, you know?

00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:02.000
The ladies and girls was wearing overalls,

00:49:02.000 --> 00:49:04.000
and they were not in their hair up,

00:49:04.000 --> 00:49:06.000
you know, napping up the hair.

00:49:06.000 --> 00:49:10.000
And so, I was on a music scholarship,

00:49:10.000 --> 00:49:12.000
and so my quiet director,

00:49:12.000 --> 00:49:14.000
who was also very rare,

00:49:14.000 --> 00:49:16.000
he was a great, wonderful quiet director,

00:49:16.000 --> 00:49:18.000
one of the greatest here.

00:49:18.000 --> 00:49:20.000
But now, was not

00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:23.000
particularly interested in movement activities, you know?

00:49:23.000 --> 00:49:25.000
So, when I,

00:49:25.000 --> 00:49:28.000
whenever we had to perform,

00:49:28.000 --> 00:49:29.000
he would pull me aside,

00:49:29.000 --> 00:49:30.000
saying, now, young lady,

00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:32.000
you're going to have to straighten that hair.

00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:35.000
You know, I could never wear my hand at your home,

00:49:35.000 --> 00:49:37.000
when we were performing, you know?

00:49:37.000 --> 00:49:40.000
So, you had that kind of mixture there, too,

00:49:40.000 --> 00:49:42.000
you had the Berenc ski tags

00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:44.000
who embrace social change

00:49:44.000 --> 00:49:48.000
and encouraged us in sociology classes, you know?

00:49:48.000 --> 00:49:51.000
And talked about social issues, you know?

00:49:51.000 --> 00:49:54.000
And so, you had the Borinskis,

00:49:54.000 --> 00:49:55.000
but then you had the towns,

00:49:55.000 --> 00:49:57.000
you had to pop a little place,

00:49:57.000 --> 00:49:58.000
and you also had,

00:49:58.000 --> 00:49:59.000
I remember one time,

00:49:59.000 --> 00:50:01.000
we actually protested on the president's line, you know?

00:50:02.000 --> 00:50:04.000
Because, the president,

00:50:04.000 --> 00:50:06.000
Dr. George A. Owens, which was very,

00:50:06.000 --> 00:50:07.000
he was very conservative,

00:50:07.000 --> 00:50:09.000
but interesting enough,

00:50:09.000 --> 00:50:12.000
he did keep up with all that went on,

00:50:12.000 --> 00:50:13.000
and it's related to movement.

00:50:13.000 --> 00:50:14.000
I had an opportunity,

00:50:14.000 --> 00:50:16.000
and I moved back here,

00:50:16.000 --> 00:50:19.000
to work in,

00:50:19.000 --> 00:50:20.000
civil-disobedience archive,

00:50:20.000 --> 00:50:21.000
a work at the archive,

00:50:21.000 --> 00:50:24.000
and I had an opportunity to work on his papers,

00:50:24.000 --> 00:50:26.000
and I actually found out,

00:50:26.000 --> 00:50:28.000
he had such a rich collection

00:50:28.000 --> 00:50:30.000
of the civil rights of,

00:50:30.000 --> 00:50:33.000
the only activities that was going on,

00:50:33.000 --> 00:50:35.000
and I actually read,

00:50:35.000 --> 00:50:36.000
and his spouse,

00:50:36.000 --> 00:50:38.000
organized in his papers,

00:50:38.000 --> 00:50:40.000
I actually got to read a lot of,

00:50:40.000 --> 00:50:42.000
the details of things that I had missed

00:50:42.000 --> 00:50:44.000
from just being out there,

00:50:44.000 --> 00:50:45.000
being an activist,

00:50:45.000 --> 00:50:47.000
and not knowing all the details of,

00:50:47.000 --> 00:50:49.000
everything that was going on.

00:50:49.000 --> 00:50:51.000
I don't think that would be very interesting.

00:50:51.000 --> 00:50:54.000
But, to be able to read those things.

00:50:54.000 --> 00:50:55.000
No, it was,

00:50:55.000 --> 00:50:56.000
I would sit there just,

00:50:56.000 --> 00:50:58.000
just when we were processing his paper,

00:50:58.000 --> 00:50:59.000
I would just sit there,

00:50:59.000 --> 00:51:02.000
and I would just really conserve it to President,

00:51:02.000 --> 00:51:04.000
kept these really rich files

00:51:04.000 --> 00:51:07.000
on all of the super-high-sacped images.

00:51:07.000 --> 00:51:09.000
So you said that you had met,

00:51:09.000 --> 00:51:11.000
like a Joyce Ladner,

00:51:11.000 --> 00:51:13.000
and some of the other women in SNCC,

00:51:13.000 --> 00:51:15.000
and you wanted to look like them?

00:51:15.000 --> 00:51:17.000
Yeah, I wanted to look like them.

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:18.000
I didn't want to.

00:51:18.000 --> 00:51:20.000
So the first thing I'd be able to do was to,

00:51:20.000 --> 00:51:22.000
I think I never,

00:51:22.000 --> 00:51:23.000
never got me in O'Boss,

00:51:23.000 --> 00:51:24.000
but I actually,

00:51:24.000 --> 00:51:25.000
yeah,

00:51:25.000 --> 00:51:27.000
I said, well, at least I could not make it there,

00:51:27.000 --> 00:51:29.000
yeah, they were like my role models.

00:51:29.000 --> 00:51:32.000
I looked up to them because they could get to do things,

00:51:32.000 --> 00:51:34.000
and when they went to O'Boss,

00:51:34.000 --> 00:51:37.000
and that sounds really, really sat down for me,

00:51:37.000 --> 00:51:40.000
because all of those big girls

00:51:40.000 --> 00:51:41.000
that was going places,

00:51:41.000 --> 00:51:44.000
they could go to Atlanta,

00:51:44.000 --> 00:51:47.000
they could go to Atlantic City,

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:52.000
and the only thing that my mom did allow me to do,

00:51:52.000 --> 00:51:54.000
I did go to my show in Washington.

00:51:54.000 --> 00:51:56.000
I thought she allowed me to go to the washroom,

00:51:56.000 --> 00:51:58.000
but I actually did go to my show.

00:51:58.000 --> 00:52:00.000
That was an interesting experience.

00:52:00.000 --> 00:52:04.000
That was an interesting experience.

00:52:04.000 --> 00:52:08.000
It was really interesting when we left out of Jackson

00:52:08.000 --> 00:52:09.000
to go to Washington.

00:52:09.000 --> 00:52:12.000
I remember my first stop within Meridian,

00:52:12.000 --> 00:52:16.000
and so we had our first stop in Meridian.

00:52:16.000 --> 00:52:18.000
And when we'd gone out of Jackson,

00:52:18.000 --> 00:52:20.000
of course, you know, we were very excited,

00:52:20.000 --> 00:52:23.000
and so, of course, we went to the rest stop,

00:52:23.000 --> 00:52:25.000
and we took color folks like that,

00:52:25.000 --> 00:52:29.000
and we didn't even think of going to the wave folks there.

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:30.000
But...

00:52:30.000 --> 00:52:31.000
I don't know.

00:52:31.000 --> 00:52:32.000
Was it a bus?

00:52:32.000 --> 00:52:33.000
We were on a bus.

00:52:33.000 --> 00:52:35.000
About six buses left out of Jackson.

00:52:35.000 --> 00:52:38.000
And so they had the bus of ministers.

00:52:38.000 --> 00:52:40.000
I remember that most of the ministers were on a bus,

00:52:40.000 --> 00:52:45.000
and they were a bus that just carried us young people,

00:52:45.000 --> 00:52:47.000
and we had chafferons, of course.

00:52:47.000 --> 00:52:50.000
But I do recall that,

00:52:50.000 --> 00:52:52.000
so when we came back,

00:52:53.000 --> 00:52:55.000
once we got to Washington,

00:52:55.000 --> 00:52:57.000
and of course, that was just so...

00:52:57.000 --> 00:52:58.000
It was just so much excitement.

00:52:58.000 --> 00:52:59.000
It was just so much going on,

00:52:59.000 --> 00:53:02.000
and so many people that as a young person,

00:53:02.000 --> 00:53:03.000
you just felt just like,

00:53:03.000 --> 00:53:06.000
I'm just happy to be a part of it, you know?

00:53:06.000 --> 00:53:10.000
And I remember that most of it was like one big picnic for me.

00:53:10.000 --> 00:53:12.000
You know, I kind of kind of sat,

00:53:12.000 --> 00:53:14.000
and I remember sitting around the monument,

00:53:14.000 --> 00:53:15.000
and putting my feet in the water,

00:53:15.000 --> 00:53:17.000
and just hanging out of me,

00:53:17.000 --> 00:53:19.000
and all the speeches.

00:53:19.000 --> 00:53:21.000
But it was so exciting.

00:53:21.000 --> 00:53:24.000
It did feel like for a young person like me,

00:53:24.000 --> 00:53:27.000
that we had...

00:53:27.000 --> 00:53:29.000
Because I was at my first...

00:53:29.000 --> 00:53:30.000
No, my first...

00:53:30.000 --> 00:53:32.000
There was my first trip about a Mississippi,

00:53:32.000 --> 00:53:36.000
but it was the first trip that ever met anything,

00:53:36.000 --> 00:53:39.000
you know, it was so, so powerful,

00:53:39.000 --> 00:53:41.000
you know, just to be in this sea of people,

00:53:41.000 --> 00:53:44.000
just to be a part of this sea of people.

00:53:44.000 --> 00:53:48.000
And so I did feel a sense of that,

00:53:48.000 --> 00:53:51.000
that in my young man,

00:53:51.000 --> 00:53:56.000
that we had done something in Washington,

00:53:56.000 --> 00:53:59.000
that we, that just by the time we went there,

00:53:59.000 --> 00:54:01.000
I met that things had changed,

00:54:01.000 --> 00:54:04.000
that we had changed Mississippi somehow,

00:54:04.000 --> 00:54:06.000
so when we came back,

00:54:06.000 --> 00:54:11.000
and we were so fired up from all of that energy,

00:54:11.000 --> 00:54:13.000
so when we came back,

00:54:13.000 --> 00:54:15.000
I mean, that same stuff in Meridian again.

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:18.000
And this time,

00:54:18.000 --> 00:54:22.000
we did not go on the color folks at.

00:54:22.000 --> 00:54:24.000
We just said that it's now...

00:54:24.000 --> 00:54:25.000
It's time.

00:54:25.000 --> 00:54:27.000
We're going to integrate, you know,

00:54:27.000 --> 00:54:31.000
so we just naturally went to the White Sad,

00:54:31.000 --> 00:54:33.000
to the restroom,

00:54:33.000 --> 00:54:36.000
and that there is a...

00:54:36.000 --> 00:54:38.000
And that people, I believe,

00:54:38.000 --> 00:54:42.000
that bus stop then had a lunch counter there,

00:54:42.000 --> 00:54:46.000
so we came, so I remember coming out of the restroom,

00:54:46.000 --> 00:54:49.000
and we came out of the restroom,

00:54:49.000 --> 00:54:52.000
a fight had broken out,

00:54:52.000 --> 00:54:56.000
so it was a group of young white thugs,

00:54:56.000 --> 00:54:58.000
and they were on motorcyclists,

00:54:58.000 --> 00:55:00.000
so they'd come in,

00:55:00.000 --> 00:55:03.000
and they began to attack the men.

00:55:03.000 --> 00:55:07.000
And so, when that happened,

00:55:07.000 --> 00:55:09.000
we were like, we don't fight back,

00:55:09.000 --> 00:55:11.000
we just came from watching on Washington,

00:55:11.000 --> 00:55:14.000
and we were not going to take no more of this here.

00:55:14.000 --> 00:55:17.000
So the menace...

00:55:17.000 --> 00:55:19.000
So what's the reason we came out of the restroom

00:55:19.000 --> 00:55:21.000
because the fate...

00:55:21.000 --> 00:55:22.000
Out of the restroom,

00:55:22.000 --> 00:55:24.000
out to the outside now,

00:55:24.000 --> 00:55:29.000
so that's when we realized the whole town

00:55:29.000 --> 00:55:32.000
of whites had come out.

00:55:32.000 --> 00:55:33.000
It was a mob,

00:55:33.000 --> 00:55:34.000
they had come out,

00:55:34.000 --> 00:55:37.000
and they actually were not in clans with the uniform,

00:55:37.000 --> 00:55:38.000
but they...

00:55:38.000 --> 00:55:39.000
It was a plan,

00:55:39.000 --> 00:55:40.000
so they were...

00:55:40.000 --> 00:55:43.000
I remember they were kind of dressed in black and white,

00:55:43.000 --> 00:55:46.000
they were not in clans uniform,

00:55:46.000 --> 00:55:49.000
and so what happened

00:55:49.000 --> 00:55:54.000
that the gang of thugs had initiated the attack,

00:55:54.000 --> 00:55:57.000
but then the mob began to throw things at us,

00:55:57.000 --> 00:55:59.000
and it was just crazy,

00:55:59.000 --> 00:56:02.000
so the menace of the gang between us,

00:56:02.000 --> 00:56:04.000
because we were in a fight,

00:56:04.000 --> 00:56:07.000
we were like, we're not going to take...

00:56:07.000 --> 00:56:08.000
At that point,

00:56:08.000 --> 00:56:11.000
it was like enough of an unbalanced,

00:56:11.000 --> 00:56:13.000
we were going to fight back, you know?

00:56:13.000 --> 00:56:17.000
And so we were actually prepared to fight back.

00:56:17.000 --> 00:56:18.000
Well, as they prepared,

00:56:18.000 --> 00:56:20.000
we were attempting to fight back,

00:56:20.000 --> 00:56:24.000
and the ministers got between us and the mob

00:56:24.000 --> 00:56:28.000
and pleaded with us to please get back on the bus fleet,

00:56:28.000 --> 00:56:30.000
so eventually they got us quite down,

00:56:30.000 --> 00:56:32.000
and we did get back on the bus,

00:56:32.000 --> 00:56:36.000
but we were told by, I guess, the chef or whoever,

00:56:36.000 --> 00:56:39.000
that we were the men here,

00:56:39.000 --> 00:56:42.000
and so we wanted to see the judge,

00:56:42.000 --> 00:56:46.000
and so they told us to come back.

00:56:46.000 --> 00:56:48.000
Sometimes I was speaking,

00:56:48.000 --> 00:56:50.000
I'm trying to remember the days

00:56:50.000 --> 00:56:52.000
that must have been the one we got back,

00:56:52.000 --> 00:56:53.000
it must have been a week in,

00:56:53.000 --> 00:56:57.000
and so we went back to Father and a week for here,

00:56:57.000 --> 00:57:02.000
and we were told that the judge was going to fish in,

00:57:02.000 --> 00:57:04.000
so we don't know if it would happen,

00:57:04.000 --> 00:57:06.000
or if nothing ever became of it,

00:57:06.000 --> 00:57:09.000
but before I left Mississippi,

00:57:09.000 --> 00:57:11.000
I mean, Megah had gotten assassinated,

00:57:11.000 --> 00:57:13.000
it's just in terms of right up front

00:57:13.000 --> 00:57:16.000
and close to things that are definitely in the violence

00:57:16.000 --> 00:57:18.000
that affected my life,

00:57:18.000 --> 00:57:21.000
and there was a young man here

00:57:21.000 --> 00:57:25.000
that got shot down and witnessed that,

00:57:25.000 --> 00:57:28.000
and down the Lynch Street,

00:57:28.000 --> 00:57:31.000
and so I think after that,

00:57:32.000 --> 00:57:35.000
and my mom actually began to get concerned,

00:57:35.000 --> 00:57:37.000
because I really was,

00:57:37.000 --> 00:57:40.000
I was angry a lot,

00:57:40.000 --> 00:57:42.000
and so my brother and I,

00:57:42.000 --> 00:57:44.000
in a group of kids,

00:57:44.000 --> 00:57:46.000
we were sometimes just,

00:57:46.000 --> 00:57:48.000
particularly after the march in Washington,

00:57:48.000 --> 00:57:50.000
and we came back,

00:57:50.000 --> 00:57:53.000
because that just steered up a different kind of anger,

00:57:53.000 --> 00:57:55.000
you know, that,

00:57:55.000 --> 00:57:58.000
and that yes, this will not start.

00:57:58.000 --> 00:58:00.000
We can continue to get beat up,

00:58:00.000 --> 00:58:02.000
and we can't fight back,

00:58:02.000 --> 00:58:04.000
and so that's what we were told,

00:58:04.000 --> 00:58:06.000
and also once there,

00:58:06.000 --> 00:58:08.000
I think we'll even be 67,

00:58:08.000 --> 00:58:11.000
when this Benjamin Brown guy shot down here on the Lynch Street,

00:58:11.000 --> 00:58:14.000
and I don't know what that approach was

00:58:14.000 --> 00:58:16.000
with the nature of that protest,

00:58:16.000 --> 00:58:18.000
but the details of it,

00:58:18.000 --> 00:58:21.000
but I do remember a march in the Lynch Street,

00:58:21.000 --> 00:58:25.000
and I do remember that,

00:58:25.000 --> 00:58:27.000
but this time the National Guard

00:58:27.000 --> 00:58:29.000
had been brought in

00:58:29.000 --> 00:58:31.000
for this demonstration for it,

00:58:31.000 --> 00:58:33.000
and I think there was something to go on

00:58:33.000 --> 00:58:35.000
over at Jackson State,

00:58:35.000 --> 00:58:39.000
when Phillip Lafayette Gibbs and James Earl Green had taken the bus,

00:58:39.000 --> 00:58:42.000
and we had two blue stoos that had left,

00:58:42.000 --> 00:58:45.000
and they had to go and just put the stoos up

00:58:45.000 --> 00:58:46.000
and that happened,

00:58:46.000 --> 00:58:47.000
which was at Jackson State.

00:58:47.000 --> 00:58:48.000
It wasn't when those groups,

00:58:48.000 --> 00:58:51.000
not when those two guys,

00:58:51.000 --> 00:58:53.000
you know, the green and,

00:58:53.000 --> 00:58:55.000
and that wasn't that,

00:58:55.000 --> 00:58:57.000
the something that has happened at Jackson State,

00:58:57.000 --> 00:58:59.000
and because Jackson State seems

00:58:59.000 --> 00:59:00.000
always been for being too.

00:59:00.000 --> 00:59:01.000
But was there one somebody

00:59:01.000 --> 00:59:04.000
that drove through the light

00:59:04.000 --> 00:59:07.000
when the lights were dry through the campus?

00:59:07.000 --> 00:59:10.000
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah,

00:59:10.000 --> 00:59:12.000
and Benjamin Brown,

00:59:12.000 --> 00:59:14.000
the Shambla,

00:59:14.000 --> 00:59:16.000
yeah, they had chosen,

00:59:16.000 --> 00:59:19.000
because I don't know the National Guard

00:59:19.000 --> 00:59:22.000
had come out on this particular march here,

00:59:22.000 --> 00:59:24.000
and this particular protest,

00:59:24.000 --> 00:59:26.000
it was a protest,

00:59:26.000 --> 00:59:28.000
right there on the street,

00:59:28.000 --> 00:59:32.000
and so in our training,

00:59:32.000 --> 00:59:34.000
someone had told us

00:59:34.000 --> 00:59:36.000
that the National Guard

00:59:36.000 --> 00:59:39.000
would not shoot

00:59:39.000 --> 00:59:42.000
unless fired upon.

00:59:42.000 --> 00:59:45.000
So a lot of us had,

00:59:45.000 --> 00:59:48.000
because of all the things that we were experiencing

00:59:48.000 --> 00:59:50.000
in terms of the brutality,

00:59:50.000 --> 00:59:52.000
you know, this was after (James) Meredith,

00:59:52.000 --> 00:59:53.000
you know,

00:59:53.000 --> 00:59:59.000
so we had began to do things

00:59:59.000 --> 01:00:02.000
that really could have gotten this key of magnitude,

01:00:02.000 --> 01:00:04.000
but then we were just young,

01:00:04.000 --> 01:00:05.000
you know, and angry.

01:00:05.000 --> 01:00:09.000
And so I think we were throwing something at them,

01:00:09.000 --> 01:00:11.000
and they turned around and said,

01:00:11.000 --> 01:00:14.000
buh-bh-bh-bh-bh-bh-bh-bh-bh-bh-bh-bh-bh-bh-bh-bh-bh-bh-bh-bh-bh-bh-bh.

01:00:14.000 --> 01:00:17.000
And so we were running into Alice,

01:00:17.000 --> 01:00:19.000
and we had a week of run,

01:00:20.000 --> 01:00:22.000
at the end of that evening,

01:00:22.000 --> 01:00:24.000
Benjamin Brown had been, been, been, been,

01:00:24.000 --> 01:00:27.000
and she killed by the National Guard.

