01:13:41.000 --> 01:13:44.000
in this urban environment that I had to find myself in, you know,

01:13:45.000 --> 01:13:48.000
that these are real issues that really happen,

01:13:48.000 --> 01:13:50.000
and that we had real programs

01:13:50.000 --> 01:13:53.000
to address those issues, you know,

01:13:53.000 --> 01:13:56.000
and ways of insisting that,

01:13:56.000 --> 01:13:58.000
one of the things that I think,

01:13:58.000 --> 01:14:01.000
that I can appreciate about the Black Pynthesis,

01:14:01.000 --> 01:14:03.000
that the, the, the,

01:14:03.000 --> 01:14:05.000
the pro-wantable things now that happens,

01:14:05.000 --> 01:14:08.000
that free breakfast in schools,

01:14:08.000 --> 01:14:10.000
were one of the programs that we initiated,

01:14:10.000 --> 01:14:12.000
you know, we were the first to initiate

01:14:13.000 --> 01:14:17.000
such a program, and, and the children had,

01:14:17.000 --> 01:14:20.000
because the whole concept is that children could not learn,

01:14:21.000 --> 01:14:25.000
adequately, if they're going to school hungry,

01:14:25.000 --> 01:14:28.000
which they were, we actually went around up children,

01:14:28.000 --> 01:14:32.000
who actually did not have breakfasts in the morning,

01:14:32.000 --> 01:14:34.000
we'd round them up and take them, you know,

01:14:34.000 --> 01:14:36.000
to the breakfast programs,

01:14:36.000 --> 01:14:41.000
and, but I actually, when you're going back to what it looks like to be a female,

01:14:42.000 --> 01:14:46.000
I actually used to do the women in the Black Pentecost,

01:14:46.000 --> 01:14:49.000
one of the big things that I do talk about a lot,

01:14:49.000 --> 01:14:52.000
and that that many of us,

01:14:52.000 --> 01:14:55.000
particularly once we began to have families,

01:14:55.000 --> 01:14:59.000
and so, so we did suffer a lot in terms of having to raise now

01:14:59.000 --> 01:15:02.000
these children on our own,

01:15:02.000 --> 01:15:05.000
and also having to be, you know,

01:15:05.000 --> 01:15:07.000
that oftentimes we were put in positions,

01:15:08.000 --> 01:15:12.000
like my going on the land was a very dangerous thing,

01:15:12.000 --> 01:15:15.000
and unsafe thing to do with the woman, you know,

01:15:15.000 --> 01:15:18.000
that it was a mother, who said mother,

01:15:18.000 --> 01:15:21.000
but it was kind of expected of us to be

01:15:21.000 --> 01:15:24.000
a guerrilla woman and mother too,

01:15:24.000 --> 01:15:26.000
you got the same time, because I mean,

01:15:26.000 --> 01:15:28.000
we looked at models, you know,

01:15:28.000 --> 01:15:32.000
the, the Battle of Algiers, you know,

01:15:32.000 --> 01:15:35.000
and, well, well, well, women actually

01:15:36.000 --> 01:15:38.000
have babies on their back in the gun,

01:15:38.000 --> 01:15:41.000
so that became a romantic kind of notion to that,

01:15:41.000 --> 01:15:44.000
that we could actually do this to be, you know,

01:15:44.000 --> 01:15:49.000
a revolutionary guerrilla and mother at the same time,

01:15:49.000 --> 01:15:52.000
you know, so those were very challenging times,

01:15:52.000 --> 01:15:56.000
and I remember, because I did try to,

01:15:56.000 --> 01:15:59.000
once I began to have family,

01:15:59.000 --> 01:16:04.000
I, I, I, I, one of my children to come first,

01:16:04.000 --> 01:16:08.000
and I remember later, he is later a,

01:16:08.000 --> 01:16:10.000
a, a, a man, a brother in the,

01:16:10.000 --> 01:16:12.000
in the black Panther Party,

01:16:12.000 --> 01:16:13.000
he said to me,

01:16:13.000 --> 01:16:14.000
lead on.

01:16:14.000 --> 01:16:16.000
That he always started with one of those bougie-type sisters,

01:16:16.000 --> 01:16:18.000
and I said, well, why would she take it with bougie?

01:16:18.000 --> 01:16:21.000
He said, because she just always seemed to be a BB,

01:16:21.000 --> 01:16:23.000
BB, BB, BB about your children,

01:16:23.000 --> 01:16:26.000
and stuff, so, you know,

01:16:26.000 --> 01:16:28.000
it was those kinds of contradictions, you know,

01:16:28.000 --> 01:16:31.000
that, that, that, that, that question, you know,

01:16:31.000 --> 01:16:33.000
it was like, okay, you're so,

01:16:33.000 --> 01:16:36.000
it's not okay to be a mother,

01:16:36.000 --> 01:16:38.000
it's not okay to, to say, well, I just want to,

01:16:38.000 --> 01:16:41.000
to, to, to spend my time making sure that these children

01:16:41.000 --> 01:16:44.000
are safe, and, you know,

01:16:44.000 --> 01:16:48.000
so, now, when you were asking, what was this question,

01:16:48.000 --> 01:16:49.000
you just asked me?

01:16:49.000 --> 01:16:51.000
What was like to be underground?

01:16:51.000 --> 01:16:53.000
I tell you,

01:16:53.000 --> 01:16:56.000
I actually never thought I would,

01:16:56.000 --> 01:17:00.000
I think the reality of being underground,

01:17:00.000 --> 01:17:04.000
and the reality of, actually, I've seen,

01:17:04.000 --> 01:17:10.000
in my life, that there's two things that I have served my team,

01:17:10.000 --> 01:17:13.000
and that is the experience that took me underground,

01:17:13.000 --> 01:17:17.000
and that it, probably was one of the greatest mystics

01:17:17.000 --> 01:17:20.000
that I've made in terms of my movement,

01:17:20.000 --> 01:17:22.000
activity, in terms of being a pantheon.

01:17:22.000 --> 01:17:25.000
It was, was, to turn in point in my life,

01:17:25.000 --> 01:17:34.000
in a sense that, that I made this decision to do something,

01:17:34.000 --> 01:17:37.000
to go against my better consciousness,

01:17:37.000 --> 01:17:40.000
that, that, that, you shouldn't do this here,

01:17:40.000 --> 01:17:42.000
you should let someone else do this here,

01:17:42.000 --> 01:17:45.000
this is not for you to do, you have children,

01:17:45.000 --> 01:17:47.000
but I think being a female again,

01:17:47.000 --> 01:17:49.000
but back to female, it, I think,

01:17:49.000 --> 01:17:51.000
it got down to a point,

01:17:51.000 --> 01:17:54.000
particularly after the split in a black train to Florida,

01:17:54.000 --> 01:17:57.000
where it was most challenging for women,

01:17:57.000 --> 01:18:00.000
because it was like being in this place,

01:18:00.000 --> 01:18:02.000
in this place, once in a split,

01:18:02.000 --> 01:18:04.000
you didn't have, I didn't have the comfort again,

01:18:04.000 --> 01:18:06.000
and it was like going from New York,

01:18:06.000 --> 01:18:08.000
from Mississippi to New York,

01:18:08.000 --> 01:18:13.000
I didn't no longer have, had to break between my life

01:18:13.000 --> 01:18:15.000
as a civil rights activist,

01:18:15.000 --> 01:18:18.000
and what do I do with my life here in New York,

01:18:18.000 --> 01:18:20.000
and having (the) Black,

01:18:20.000 --> 01:18:23.000
a panther party, now, of, very short limbs,

01:18:23.000 --> 01:18:25.000
we were talking about a very short-lived experience,

01:18:25.000 --> 01:18:28.000
because (the) Black played a part of his 68,

01:18:28.000 --> 01:18:33.000
so in, in 1971, there was no longer an organized organization,

01:18:33.000 --> 01:18:36.000
so again, it is what do I do with my life now,

01:18:36.000 --> 01:18:38.000
movement has been moving my life now,

01:18:38.000 --> 01:18:41.000
and so we were just pulled,

01:18:41.000 --> 01:18:44.000
and just pulled in all kinds of directions,

01:18:44.000 --> 01:18:48.000
and, and I did come home to Mississippi in 1971

01:18:48.000 --> 01:18:49.000
to try to regroup,

01:18:49.000 --> 01:18:52.000
but the, uh, uh, uh,

01:18:52.000 --> 01:18:55.000
powers that be, was not going to have that,

01:18:55.000 --> 01:18:58.000
because, um, I was, uh, once I came home,

01:18:58.000 --> 01:19:00.000
I brought,

01:19:00.000 --> 01:19:02.000
danger home to my family,

01:19:02.000 --> 01:19:03.000
as my mother was put,

01:19:03.000 --> 01:19:04.000
you know, that's,

01:19:04.000 --> 01:19:05.000
so my family felt about me,

01:19:05.000 --> 01:19:07.000
that I had brought danger,

01:19:07.000 --> 01:19:08.000
I didn't invite danger,

01:19:08.000 --> 01:19:10.000
danger followed me here,

01:19:10.000 --> 01:19:13.000
because, uh, a female again,

01:19:13.000 --> 01:19:14.000
it's like,

01:19:14.000 --> 01:19:16.000
if you're female, then you know

01:19:16.000 --> 01:19:17.000
what the system is,

01:19:17.000 --> 01:19:21.000
and so, you know what's going on with these men folks,

01:19:21.000 --> 01:19:25.000
and so, so, so danger followed me here to Mississippi,

01:19:25.000 --> 01:19:28.000
and, um, so I stayed in Mississippi,

01:19:28.000 --> 01:19:30.000
uh, uh, got uncomfortable,

01:19:30.000 --> 01:19:32.000
and I, I felt,

01:19:32.000 --> 01:19:35.000
no, I don't want to expose my family to this,

01:19:35.000 --> 01:19:37.000
I don't want to expose all of the people,

01:19:37.000 --> 01:19:40.000
you know, that I've gone to school with,

01:19:40.000 --> 01:19:41.000
and I exposed to,

01:19:41.000 --> 01:19:44.000
to the kind of COINTELPRO terrorism

01:19:44.000 --> 01:19:46.000
that was going on during that period,

01:19:46.000 --> 01:19:49.000
and there wasn't so much anything that I had done,

01:19:49.000 --> 01:19:51.000
it was supposedly who I knew,

01:19:51.000 --> 01:19:53.000
and so that kind of fresh,

01:19:53.000 --> 01:19:55.000
I found myself back in New York,

01:19:55.000 --> 01:19:56.000
and, um,

01:19:56.000 --> 01:19:58.000
what followed that is still,

01:19:58.000 --> 01:20:00.000
I'm just still feeling kind of displaced,

01:20:00.000 --> 01:20:02.000
it's like,

01:20:02.000 --> 01:20:04.000
movement is the life that I've known,

01:20:04.000 --> 01:20:06.000
and so, what do I do,

01:20:06.000 --> 01:20:08.000
and so, I did find myself

01:20:08.000 --> 01:20:11.000
gravitating to more the radical wing of the,

01:20:11.000 --> 01:20:13.000
of the split in the party,

01:20:13.000 --> 01:20:17.000
and so, so, an incident in 1971,

01:20:17.000 --> 01:20:21.000
uh, uh, set me on the run.

01:20:21.000 --> 01:20:22.000
In the floor?

01:20:22.000 --> 01:20:24.000
Yes, it did set me on the run,

01:20:24.000 --> 01:20:27.000
but it was an incident in which I,

01:20:27.000 --> 01:20:28.000
and my better judgment say,

01:20:28.000 --> 01:20:29.000
don't do that,

01:20:29.000 --> 01:20:30.000
because that's not the,

01:20:30.000 --> 01:20:32.000
you have the children in there,

01:20:32.000 --> 01:20:33.000
but, however,

01:20:33.000 --> 01:20:34.000
it did set me on the run,

01:20:34.000 --> 01:20:36.000
and so, so I stayed,

01:20:36.000 --> 01:20:39.000
uh, I had my baby on the ground,

01:20:39.000 --> 01:20:40.000
my baby daughter,

01:20:40.000 --> 01:20:42.000
it was born on the ground,

01:20:42.000 --> 01:20:44.000
and, um, so,

01:20:44.000 --> 01:20:47.000
there was a, a, um,

01:20:47.000 --> 01:20:49.000
I think, having a,

01:20:49.000 --> 01:20:52.000
having a child on the ground,

01:20:52.000 --> 01:20:53.000
I was, you know,

01:20:53.000 --> 01:20:54.000
it was a, ye,

01:20:54.000 --> 01:20:57.000
I had to go into,

01:20:57.000 --> 01:20:59.000
to, to, to a,

01:20:59.000 --> 01:21:00.000
a safe area,

01:21:00.000 --> 01:21:01.000
with, with, with,

01:21:01.000 --> 01:21:02.000
a group of,

01:21:02.000 --> 01:21:03.000
my birth's what?

01:21:03.000 --> 01:21:04.000
It was with white women,

01:21:04.000 --> 01:21:06.000
whether I'm the ground of people,

01:21:06.000 --> 01:21:08.000
and, um, so,

01:21:08.000 --> 01:21:11.000
I stayed there until I had my,

01:21:11.000 --> 01:21:12.560
until I had my baby.

01:21:12.560 --> 01:21:18.760
And once I had my child, I had to make a decision of now.

01:21:18.760 --> 01:21:20.920
So it was a turning point in my life.

01:21:20.920 --> 01:21:23.560
So I did have to make a decision that,

01:21:23.560 --> 01:21:26.120
because this is very, very dangerous now.

01:21:26.120 --> 01:21:28.720
This is where life had really gotten dangerous

01:21:28.720 --> 01:21:31.760
in the sense that, wow, this is life-threatening dangerous,

01:21:31.760 --> 01:21:34.520
because now people that are at that out of us

01:21:34.520 --> 01:21:38.560
are getting killed, they're going away,

01:21:38.560 --> 01:21:41.160
and they're not coming back, they either going to jail,

01:21:41.160 --> 01:21:42.760
they're getting killed.

01:21:42.760 --> 01:21:48.640
And so what I eventually had to do was to just separate myself,

01:21:48.640 --> 01:21:51.040
to protect myself, you know?

01:21:51.040 --> 01:21:57.320
And so, so, so, that is pretty much it was rough.

01:21:57.320 --> 01:21:59.280
To say the least, it was rough.

01:21:59.280 --> 01:22:04.840
I managed to get my children back, back with me.

01:22:04.840 --> 01:22:09.640
The two older ones were family members,

01:22:09.640 --> 01:22:11.040
so I managed to get them back,

01:22:11.040 --> 01:22:13.880
because that was the most depressing thing

01:22:13.880 --> 01:22:17.080
that I had this experience was to be separated

01:22:17.080 --> 01:22:19.640
to have my children, you know, here and there,

01:22:19.640 --> 01:22:20.800
and not with me.

01:22:20.800 --> 01:22:24.640
And so, so I managed to get my children back together,

01:22:24.640 --> 01:22:30.800
and I managed to survive underground by, by, you know,

01:22:30.800 --> 01:22:37.600
networking and creating my own support system in the sense of,

01:22:37.600 --> 01:22:44.200
and so, four years, I lived four years underground,

01:22:44.200 --> 01:22:50.000
and my children, knowing that I could not,

01:22:50.000 --> 01:22:55.600
my children would grow up not knowing their grandparents

01:22:55.600 --> 01:22:57.840
and not being able to have a normal life

01:22:57.840 --> 01:22:59.240
like other children.

01:22:59.240 --> 01:23:02.840
All of that went into play in terms of,

01:23:02.840 --> 01:23:04.200
of me making a decision,

01:23:04.200 --> 01:23:06.880
or how do I get myself out of this situation

01:23:06.880 --> 01:23:11.400
that I found myself in, and how bad it actually to really look at

01:23:11.400 --> 01:23:15.320
how bad this situation is, and what are my options.

01:23:15.320 --> 01:23:18.160
And so, I did after four years of that life,

01:23:18.160 --> 01:23:20.600
I began to explore my options,

01:23:20.600 --> 01:23:23.400
of, of, of, of, clearing myself

01:23:23.400 --> 01:23:26.520
of the situation that landed me there.

01:23:26.560 --> 01:23:30.320
And so, I did get a lawyer to look into it,

01:23:30.320 --> 01:23:34.400
and so I was able to, to get myself clear out of the situation

01:23:34.400 --> 01:23:36.280
with pretty much a little slap on the hand,

01:23:36.280 --> 01:23:40.720
pretty much, and because it was not as bad of a situation

01:23:40.720 --> 01:23:43.240
as the South of Chicago situation,

01:23:43.240 --> 01:23:45.360
not of that, not of that stuff having,

01:23:45.360 --> 01:23:47.800
but it was a turbulent time for life,

01:23:47.800 --> 01:23:51.960
because then I had to always be looking at all my shoulders.

01:23:51.960 --> 01:23:55.880
I never knew, you know, when the day that I might be gone down,

01:23:55.880 --> 01:23:58.640
I never knew that the day might come,

01:23:58.640 --> 01:24:01.040
that I might get arrested and told for my children,

01:24:01.040 --> 01:24:04.680
and that is the kind of life that I had to leave, you know.

01:24:04.680 --> 01:24:07.280
I remember one day going to supermarket,

01:24:07.280 --> 01:24:10.160
and I saw some police officers in it,

01:24:10.160 --> 01:24:12.320
and I was like, oh, and they were looking at me,

01:24:12.320 --> 01:24:14.520
and then I was like, this is the day.

01:24:14.520 --> 01:24:16.760
And so, so it was that kind of life

01:24:16.760 --> 01:24:19.320
of always feeling that this is the day.

01:24:19.320 --> 01:24:22.720
And so, that was four years of that,

01:24:22.720 --> 01:24:26.160
and then once I got myself cleared up,

01:24:26.160 --> 01:24:31.160
my husband ended up in the biggest mess,

01:24:31.160 --> 01:24:35.040
and so I ended up doing, instead of two years' probation,

01:24:35.040 --> 01:24:38.280
then I ended up in the whole five years

01:24:38.280 --> 01:24:40.880
because of that man they call my husband,

01:24:40.880 --> 01:24:45.880
that's what I was told, you know, so it was, yeah.

01:24:45.880 --> 01:24:50.280
So, I think you had something else.

01:24:50.280 --> 01:24:51.120
But, I don't think that's the answer,

01:24:51.120 --> 01:24:52.680
are there any final thoughts you have,

01:24:52.680 --> 01:24:54.640
or things that you would want young people,

01:24:54.640 --> 01:24:57.000
or others to know about your work,

01:24:57.000 --> 01:24:59.760
civil rights, human rights, in the specificity

01:24:59.760 --> 01:25:01.200
with the panthers?

01:25:01.200 --> 01:25:03.200
Well, I think I would, young people,

01:25:03.200 --> 01:25:06.160
I often try to tell them that stand up for something,

01:25:06.160 --> 01:25:09.000
okay, that, that, if you don't stand for something,

01:25:09.000 --> 01:25:14.000
you know, that, you know, that's why I do try to,

01:25:14.280 --> 01:25:17.280
to encourage young people, but I also want them to,

01:25:17.280 --> 01:25:20.360
to think, okay, because much of my environment,

01:25:20.360 --> 01:25:21.920
particularly with the panthers,

01:25:21.920 --> 01:25:26.040
and stuff, had much to do with, I mean,

01:25:26.040 --> 01:25:28.760
when we were an organized organization,

01:25:29.720 --> 01:25:34.000
I felt that there was something that gave me me,

01:25:34.000 --> 01:25:36.080
and some fulfillment in my life,

01:25:36.080 --> 01:25:37.840
and that I was doing things that kind of,

01:25:37.840 --> 01:25:39.320
concretely, could make a difference,

01:25:39.320 --> 01:25:41.200
and that, yes, that, that, that,

01:25:41.200 --> 01:25:44.600
if we are going to, to be here, you know,

01:25:44.600 --> 01:25:46.080
since we are here on this earth,

01:25:46.080 --> 01:25:48.120
and this journey, that we should,

01:25:48.120 --> 01:25:50.280
find something to make a difference, you know,

01:25:50.280 --> 01:25:52.840
that it just, just be, you know,

01:25:52.840 --> 01:25:56.160
and to know what it is, you know,

01:25:56.160 --> 01:25:58.560
that you can do, what it is that you,

01:25:58.560 --> 01:26:00.560
yourself, can do to make a difference,

01:26:00.560 --> 01:26:03.760
and not the blindly following, you know,

01:26:03.760 --> 01:26:05.640
so, so I think, you know, that,

01:26:05.640 --> 01:26:07.360
that's one of the things that is encouraged,

01:26:07.360 --> 01:26:09.360
not the blindly following, and,

01:26:09.360 --> 01:26:13.080
that, that, a lot of young people,

01:26:13.080 --> 01:26:15.120
particularly when it comes to the panthers,

01:26:15.120 --> 01:26:18.160
a lot of young people want to know about the panthers,

01:26:18.160 --> 01:26:21.160
but, but, there's the romanticism,

01:26:21.160 --> 01:26:25.240
so, so, basically, I want to know the good,

01:26:25.240 --> 01:26:27.040
the bad, and the ugly, you know,

01:26:27.040 --> 01:26:29.120
that, that, I advise young people,

01:26:29.120 --> 01:26:32.640
when studying the movement, to, to,

01:26:32.640 --> 01:26:35.360
what I found is that, that, that, now,

01:26:35.360 --> 01:26:37.800
even with doing this interview here,

01:26:38.760 --> 01:26:40.840
I'm wondering how much,

01:26:45.120 --> 01:26:47.480
do we, what do we, we tell people that,

01:26:47.480 --> 01:26:49.720
that, that, that, that, young people tend to think that,

01:26:49.720 --> 01:26:51.560
that, that, we were just kind of born,

01:26:51.560 --> 01:26:54.560
that, that, that we did super things,

